answers.body_markdown:
You have an UB here:

    SqQueue myCircularQueueCreate(int k) {
        MyCircularQueue Queue;  // stack allocation
        SqQueue Q=&amp;Queue;
        Q-&gt;size=k;
        /* ... */
        return Q;  // returning the address of a stack object
    }

Once you finished that function, the allocated structure is deallocated

Here

    SqQueue myCircularQueueCreate(int k) {
        MyCircularQueue Queue;
        SqQueue Q=&amp;Queue;
        ...
        ...
        return Q;
    }

you return the address of a local variable. That variable stop to exist when the function returns. So using the pointer afterwards accesses an object that no longer exists in the system.

Use dynamic allocation instead of a local variable, i.e.

    SqQueue Q =malloc(sizeof *Q);

BTW: `typedef` of pointers are often considered a bad idea.

